"Some of the frogs that we're about to lose are really amazing."

Scientists have identified 26 Australian frog species at great risk of extinction by 2040, with at least four species already feared gone.

They say unless urgent action is taken now, the rest are unlikely to make it.

#Frogs #Australia #BBCNews

node.title: Saving Australian frogs on the brink of extinction

More countries are now offering teenagers coronavirus vaccines – but not all parents are allowing their children to get immunised.

The US support group Teens for Vaccines - which is run by teenagers for teenagers - says young people around the world are being left out of discussions that affect their own health.

Meanwhile in the UK, vaccine experts recommended on Friday not to give the jab to all 12-15 year olds, although the chief medical officers may take a different approach.

#Covid #Coronavirus #Health #BBCNews

node.title: 'My parents won't let me get the Covid vaccine'

Prof Kim Hyung-suk is a 102-year-old Professor who comes from the same village as the original ‘Great Leader’ of North Korea, Kim Il-Sung. 

In 1945, after Japan was expelled from Korea he had breakfast with the man who would go on to be the first leader of North Korea and the founding father of the Kim dynasty which still holds power to this day.

#BBCNews #NorthKorea

Swedish pop superstars Abba have surprised and delighted fans by announcing their first studio album for 40 years.

Abba Voyage will be released in November, before a "revolutionary" set of concerts where virtual avatars will play hits like Mamma Mia and Waterloo.

The quartet, who split up in 1982, said they ended up back in the recording studio while working on the stage show.

"At first it was just two songs, and then we said, 'Well, maybe we should do a few others,'" said Benny Andersson.

#Abba #AbbaMusic #BBCNews

node.title: Pop legends Abba announce new music

A state of emergency has been declared in New York City and New Jersey after they were hit by record rainfall and flash flooding as a result of Tropical Storm Ida.

“I just want a fair chance and a fair shot to compete at my highest level.”

US athlete Blake Leeper, a double amputee, is already a Paralympic silver medallist and world record holder - and now wants to compete in the Olympics.

But after the rules were changed in 2018, the blades that Leeper had been running on for years were deemed too long for competition.

Instead of shortening his blades, Blake took World Athletics to the Court of Arbitration for Sport, arguing their measuring system was not only “discriminatory”, but that he believed the Olympics was simply “not ready for a disabled man, not only to compete, but win".

He lost his case. Meanwhile, World Athletics strongly denies his allegation that the rules are discriminatory based on race.

#Olympics #BBCNews

node.title: Why was this athlete 'too tall' to race?

node.text:
After 12 hours of surgery a pair of one-year-old twin girls were finally able to look at one-another, having been born conjoined at the back of the head.
 
The duo underwent a rare separation surgery in Israel, which has only been conducted 20 times worldwide and took months of preparation.

"They are breathing and eating on their own," Eldad Silberstein, the head of Soroka's plastic surgery department, told Israel's Channel 12 news.

Tap the link in our bio for more on the girls and their recovery.

(📷 Reuters)

node.text:
Girls Aloud singer Sarah Harding, who had breast cancer, has died at the age of 39.
 
Her mother Marie announced the news on Instagram, describing her "beautiful" daughter as "a bright, shining star".
 
Earlier this year, Harding revealed doctors had told her she would not see another Christmas.
 
In a post next to a black and white image, Marie wrote: "It's with deep heartbreak that today I'm sharing the news that my beautiful daughter Sarah has sadly passed away.
 
"I'd like to thank everyone for their kind support over the past year. It meant the world to Sarah and it gave her great strength and comfort to know she was loved."
 
Tap the link in our bio to read more about Harding's life.
 
(PHOTO 1: PA Media, PHOTO 2: With Girls Aloud in 2009, PA Media)

node.text:
The traditional sari is being re-interpreted by a new generation

For their parents generation a sari wearing woman is more modest, delicate and respectful but in recent years, designers, artists and influencers have been challenging the traditional feminine ideals attached to the garment.

With innovative styles introduced by young South Asian women, the sari is making a comeback as everyday clothing. Designers and stylists are moving away from conventional sari draping; they wrap it around jeans instead of the petticoat, and wear it over a t-shirt instead of the tailored blouse.

Tap the link in the bio to read more about how sari’s are being worn by a new generation

More countries are now offering teenagers coronavirus vaccines – but not all parents are allowing their children to get immunised.

The US support group Teens for Vaccines - which is run by teenagers for teenagers - says young people around the world are being left out of discussions that affect their own health.

Meanwhile in the UK, vaccine experts recommended on Friday not to give the jab to all 12-15 year olds, although the chief medical officers may take a different approach.

node.text:
Temperatures across Europe in 2020 were more than 1.9c above the average, and were the highest since records began in 1900.

The State of the Climate 2020 report from the American Meteorological Society says the scale of the record-breaking heat in Europe is troubling, and the temperatures in the Arctic are also rising rapidly.

Profesoor Gabi Hegerl, of climate system science at the University of Edinburgh, who was not involved with the study, says the findings should “worry us all” and that scientists cannot stress “how unusual this warmth is."

Tap the link in our bio to read the key findings from the State of the Climate report.

(📷 Getty Images)
